  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3eb7d353-def1-41ee-815e-20ae9c8fd210",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Final project \n",
    "# The housing project"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "325395ef-e507-4707-80d0-71ba62e06338",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Introduction: \n",
    "Currently I am a 2nd year economics and finance student and last semester I had a very interesting course called \"Money, banking and financial markets\". In this course we talked a lot about how interest rates affect the world and how it works as a tool to make people spend more or less, whatever is best for the economy.\n",
    "\n",
    "The idea is the following:\n",
    "When there is high inflation that generally means that people have a lot of money on their hands and spend a lot. That causes prices of good and services to rise. To prevent inflation going higher, central banks raise their interest rates so people don't borrow as much. When interest rate go high, borrowing money becomes more expensive and people borrow less. This process aims to \"cool down\" the economy. \n",
    "\n",
    "That is in theory, but I was curious of how that effect is felt around the world as housing prices aren't all the same around the world. I also thought if there was a different affect for some countries and not others, if perhaps some are more reliant on mortgages than others.\n",
    "\n",
    "This was a very interesting notion to me and in this project I aim to analyze how different interest rates and inflation rates affect the housing prices in developed and developing countries. \n",
    "\n",
    "Limitation: Developing countries don't always have the most reliant data. Those countries also have more recent data, so our scope will be in the 21st century. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "67ec3bbd-02ad-4b47-a74a-3c887597319e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# The hypothesis I go into this project are the following:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fe2c0bbe-00f3-445c-8cb1-cc0f95a325f5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "H1: Interest rates affect housing prices equally across countries"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d0292378-b3fa-45ed-93da-5d4c7cc2bb8c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "H2: The affect of interest rates is stronger in developed countries,than in developing countries"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "87b794c9-41e3-4c16-aced-1691d90e63dc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# The steps I aim to make for this project:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "72daff6a-db1b-4bd1-9bb2-7860efcea48d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "1. Gather and clean data about: Housing prices, Interest rates, Income levels and Inflation\n",
    "2. Clean and merge them into 1 big data set\n",
    "3. Divide data for developing and developed countries\n",
    "4. Analyze trends per group over the years\n",
    "5. Run a regression analysis on every group\n",
    "6. Compare and Analyze - confirm or deny H1 AND H2\n",
    "7. Summary of the project"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ce1d25fa-8fdc-4d43-8676-60d42128b60e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Data used:\n",
    "When adding new data, I will be adding it here. If explanation is need about the data, it will be provided here.\n",
    "1. Residential property prices - index , real(adjusted for inflation) , 2000 - 2025, quarterly ([Bis.data.org](https://data.bis.org/topics/RPP/data?data_view=table&rows=REF_AREA&cols=TIME_PERIOD&settings=asc%7Cdesc%7Cname&filter=FREQ%3DQ%255EUNIT_MEASURE%3D628%255EVALUE%3DR%255EYEAR%3D2000%257C2001%257C2002%257C2003%257C2004%257C2005%257C2006%257C2007%257C2008%257C2009%257C2010%257C2011%257C2012%257C2013%257C2014%257C2015%257C2016%257C2017%257C2018%257C2019%257C2021%257C2020%257C2022%257C2025%257C2024%257C2023))\n",
    "- The data is 'real', which means it's adjusted for inflation - we only look at the real change for the period"
   ]
  },
